        -:   82:/** \ingroup SparseLU_Module
        -:   83:  * \class SparseLU
        -:   84:  * 
        -:   85:  * \brief Sparse supernodal LU factorization for general matrices
        -:   86:  * 
        -:   87:  * This class implements the supernodal LU factorization for general matrices.
        -:   88:  * It uses the main techniques from the sequential SuperLU package 
        -:   89:  * (http://crd-legacy.lbl.gov/~xiaoye/SuperLU/). It handles transparently real 
        -:   90:  * and complex arithmetic with single and double precision, depending on the 
        -:   91:  * scalar type of your input matrix. 
        -:   92:  * The code has been optimized to provide BLAS-3 operations during supernode-panel updates. 
        -:   93:  * It benefits directly from the built-in high-performant Eigen BLAS routines. 
        -:   94:  * Moreover, when the size of a supernode is very small, the BLAS calls are avoided to 
        -:   95:  * enable a better optimization from the compiler. For best performance, 
        -:   96:  * you should compile it with NDEBUG flag to avoid the numerous bounds checking on vectors. 
        -:   97:  * 
        -:   98:  * An important parameter of this class is the ordering method. It is used to reorder the columns 
        -:   99:  * (and eventually the rows) of the matrix to reduce the number of new elements that are created during 
        -:  100:  * numerical factorization. The cheapest method available is COLAMD. 
        -:  101:  * See  \link OrderingMethods_Module the OrderingMethods module \endlink for the list of 
        -:  102:  * built-in and external ordering methods. 
        -:  103:  *
        -:  104:  * Simple example with key steps 
        -:  105:  * \code
        -:  106:  * VectorXd x(n), b(n);
        -:  107:  * SparseMatrix<double> A;
        -:  108:  * SparseLU<SparseMatrix<double>, COLAMDOrdering<int> >   solver;
        -:  109:  * // fill A and b;
        -:  110:  * // Compute the ordering permutation vector from the structural pattern of A
        -:  111:  * solver.analyzePattern(A); 
        -:  112:  * // Compute the numerical factorization 
        -:  113:  * solver.factorize(A); 
        -:  114:  * //Use the factors to solve the linear system 
        -:  115:  * x = solver.solve(b); 
        -:  116:  * \endcode
        -:  117:  * 
        -:  118:  * \warning The input matrix A should be in a \b compressed and \b column-major form.
        -:  119:  * Otherwise an expensive copy will be made. You can call the inexpensive makeCompressed() to get a compressed matrix.
        -:  120:  * 
        -:  121:  * \note Unlike the initial SuperLU implementation, there is no step to equilibrate the matrix. 
        -:  122:  * For badly scaled matrices, this step can be useful to reduce the pivoting during factorization. 
        -:  123:  * If this is the case for your matrices, you can try the basic scaling method at
        -:  124:  *  "unsupported/Eigen/src/IterativeSolvers/Scaling.h"
        -:  125:  * 
        -:  126:  * \tparam MatrixType_ The type of the sparse matrix. It must be a column-major SparseMatrix<>
        -:  127:  * \tparam OrderingType_ The ordering method to use, either AMD, COLAMD or METIS. Default is COLMAD
        -:  128:  *
        -:  129:  * \implsparsesolverconcept
        -:  130:  * 
        -:  131:  * \sa \ref TutorialSparseSolverConcept
        -:  132:  * \sa \ref OrderingMethods_Module
        -:  133:  */
        -:  134:template <typename MatrixType_, typename OrderingType_>
        -:  135:class SparseLU : public SparseSolverBase<SparseLU<MatrixType_,OrderingType_> >, public internal::SparseLUImpl<typename MatrixType_::Scalar, typename MatrixType_::StorageIndex>
